%N A395472 Decimal expansion of the angle theta (in radians) such that 5*theta and 3*theta are the half central angles of the circular arcs of a constructible squarable lune.
%C A395472 The angle in degrees is 16.793... . The two half central angles are 5*theta = 1.465... = 83.969... degrees, and 3*theta = 0.879... = 50.381... degrees.
%C A395472 See A395465 for details, references and more links.
%H A395472 Amiram Eldar, <a href="/A395468/a395468.png">Illustration</a>.
%H A395472 Mikhail Mikhailovich Postnikov, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/2589121">The Problem of Squarable Lunes</a>, The American Mathematical Monthly, Vol. 107, No. 7 (2000), pp. 645-651. Translated from Russian by Abe Shenitzer.
%H A395472 <a href="/index/Tra#transcendental">Index entries for transcendental numbers</a>.
%F A395472 Equals arccos((sqrt(5/3) - 1 + sqrt(20/3 + sqrt(20/3)))/4)/2.
%e A395472 0.293109197301404358232893099155098839281045160270675...
%t A395472 RealDigits[ArcCos[(Sqrt[5/3] - 1 + Sqrt[20/3 + Sqrt[20/3]])/4]/2, 10, 120][[1]]
%o A395472 (PARI) acos((sqrt(5/3) - 1 + sqrt(20/3 + sqrt(20/3)))/4)/2
